    "reasoning_content": "Okay, let's tackle the user's question: \"Who are the top 2 customers by total order amount?\" \n\nFirst, I need to figure out which tables and columns are involved. The available tables are Customer and SalesOrder. The Customer table probably has customer information, and SalesOrder would have order details. To find the total order amount per customer, I'll need to link these two tables.\n\nI should check the schema to confirm the columns. The Customer table likely has a customer_id, and the SalesOrder table would have a customer_id foreign key, along with an amount column. But wait, the user mentioned \"total order amount,\" so maybe the SalesOrder table has an order_amount or similar column. \n\nSince I don't have the schema yet, I should call get_database_schema to understand the structure. Once I have the schema, I can determine the correct columns to join and aggregate.\n\nAssuming the schema shows that SalesOrder has customer_id and order_amount, the next step is to sum the order amounts per customer. Then, order those sums in descending order and pick the top 2. \n\nI'll need to join Customer and SalesOrder on customer_id, sum the order amounts, group by customer, then order by the sum descending. Finally, limit to 2 results. \n\nBut wait, the user might want the customer names, so the Customer table should have a name column. So the query would select customer.name, sum(order.amount), group by customer.id, order by sum desc, limit 2. \n\nI should also check if there are any other relevant columns or if there are multiple tables involved. Let me start by getting the schema to confirm the exact column names and relationships.\n",
